# Plan: Add "mistral-instruct-v3" Chat Template Handler

## Context

The llama.cpp codebase has a legacy chat template system that uses an enum-based approach (`llm_chat_template`) to register, auto-detect, and apply chat templates for different model families. There are already five Mistral handlers: `mistral-v1`, `mistral-v3`, `mistral-v3-tekken`, `mistral-v7`, and `mistral-v7-tekken`. The task is to add a sixth handler for the Mistral Instruct v0.3 format — a simpler variant that uses `[INST]`/`[/INST]` markers with system messages prepended to the first user turn and `</s>` after assistant turns, without `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` tags or `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` support.

## Files to Modify

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `src/llama-chat.h` (line 60) | Add new enum value |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` (lines ~80, ~120, ~902) | Add name mapping, detection, and handler |
| `tests/test-chat-template.cpp` (line ~628) | Add test case |

## Step-by-step Implementation

### Step 1: Add enum value to `src/llama-chat.h`

Insert a new enum entry `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3` just before the existing `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN` (line 61). This groups it with the other Mistral entries conceptually, while keeping it at the end (before UNKNOWN) to avoid changing any existing enum ordinal values.

```cpp
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_SOLAR_OPEN,
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,  // <-- NEW
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN,
```

### Step 2: Add name mapping in `src/llama-chat.cpp`

Add a new entry to the `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATES` map (after the existing `solar-open` entry, around line 80):

```cpp
    { "solar-open",        LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_SOLAR_OPEN        },
    { "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },  // <-- NEW
};
```

This enables direct name-based lookup via `llm_chat_template_from_str("mistral-instruct-v3")`.

### Step 3: Add auto-detection heuristic in `llm_chat_detect_template()`

The detection logic lives in a nested if-else tree inside the `[INST]` branch (lines 103-137). The current structure:

```
if tmpl_contains("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") → v7
else if tmpl_contains("' [INST] ' + system_message") || tmpl_contains("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]") → v1/v3/v3-tekken
else → llama2 variants
```

Insert a **new `else if`** between the v1/v3/v3-tekken block (line 120) and the llama2 `else` block (line 121). The detection check:

```cpp
            return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_V3;
        } else if (tmpl_contains("system_message")) {
            // Mistral Instruct v0.3 — [INST]/[/INST] with system prepended, no [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
            return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
        } else {
            // llama2 template and its variants
```

**Why `tmpl_contains("system_message")` works here:**
- At this point in the tree, `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` is already ruled out (v7 check, line 104)
- `' [INST] ' + system_message` is already ruled out (v1 check, line 108) — note leading space
- `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` is ruled out (v3 check, line 110)
- A Mistral Instruct v0.3 Jinja template uses a `system_message` variable (e.g., `'[INST] ' + system_message + '\n\n'`) but WITHOUT the leading-space pattern that v1 uses
- Basic llama2 templates do NOT contain `system_message`; llama2-sys variants use `<<SYS>>` tags instead
- This distinguishes from the Ministral 3 / v7 handler because `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` is absent

### Step 4: Add template handler in `llm_chat_apply_template()`

Add a new `else if` block before the final `else { return -1; }` block (before line 903):

```cpp
    } else if (tmpl == LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3) {
        // Mistral Instruct v0.3 template
        // See: https://huggingface.co/mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3
        bool is_inside_turn = false;
        for (auto message : chat) {
            if (!is_inside_turn) {
                ss << "[INST] ";
                is_inside_turn = true;
            }
            std::string role(message->role);
            std::string content(message->content);
            if (role == "system") {
                ss << content << "\n\n";
            } else if (role == "user") {
                ss << content << " [/INST]";
            } else {
                ss << content << "</s>";
                is_inside_turn = false;
            }
        }
    } else {
        // template not supported
        return -1;
    }
```

**Format produced:**
- System message prepended to first user turn: `[INST] {system}\n\n{user} [/INST]`
- Normal user turn: `[INST] {user} [/INST]`
- Assistant turn: `{content}</s>`
- No leading space before `[INST]` (unlike v1)
- No assistant message trimming (unlike v3)
- Space after `[INST]` and before `[/INST]`

### Step 5: Add test case in `tests/test-chat-template.cpp`

Add a new test case entry to the `test_cases` vector, after the last existing entry (granite-4.0 at line 628):

```cpp
        {
